snippet.textDisplay:
Light aircraft all have Hobbs meters. Almost all aircraft also have their circuit breakers out of immediate FoV, maybe by the leg or behind and above the head. They're designed to pop out so when something happens a pilot can rapidly sweep their hand across the breaker panel and determine a breaker fault while also contending with over potential nightmares and flying the plane at the same time.
When flying we always check two meters, Hobbs and Tach. Why are there two time meters in the aircraft? "The tachometer [time] only matches the Hobbs meter when the aircraft is operating at cruise. When you pull back the throttle and lean the mixture, the propeller's RPM slows, which slows the tachometer. The difference between the Hobbs meter and tachometer [time] is greatest when descending and landing."

snippet.textDisplay:
Wow. You did it. You reviewed the Vector.

One word sums up this car. Overreach.

Weigert was trying to build a Bugatti Veyron 30 years before the technology existed. That he got this far, and achieved this much, without the backing of a corporate behemoth like Volkswagen, makes you wonder what he might have done with serious finance behind him.

But yes, I've wanted to see this car reviewed, because it does look like it's materialised from a planet on the far side of the galaxy. I want to see the looks on everyone's faces when this thing is parked in a supermarket car park. It's the archetype of 80's spaceship excess.

snippet.textDisplay:
The german wikipedia has some interesting and funny facts to the car (actually a lot more than the english version of the article). For example, the air outlets in the cockpit are also used in an F/A-18, the multi-function screen is from an M1 Abrams Tank and due to a marketing contract with Blaupunkt, there were more then a dozen of speakers built into the interior even tho some of them weren't even connected to the head unit. :-D
Great video, curious for the second part!

snippet.textDisplay: Doug said that he guessed they (Vector) cheaped out on the forwards and backwards seat adjuster by making it manually operated.  I'm 99% sure they did that to allow the seat to sit lower to the floor.  Manually operated seats take up less space, so even just omitting the power forwards/backwards capability they  saved some space and allowed the seat to sit much lower than It would have otherwise.
